Based on everything I have seen, the standard way to connect vertices (or nodes - however you want to call them) together is by creating an edge which contains the &quot;from&quot; vertex and to &quot;to&quot; vertex. There are a few different ways of representing this connection (`adjacency list`, `adjacency matrix`, `incident matrix`, etc.).

Edges (and vertices) can be given `labels` to give identity / value to the edge. They can also be given a `weight` (which might be considered the same as a `label` but from what I&#39;ve seen - there is a difference).

implementing an `adjacency list` with edges having `labels` would essentially look as follows (pseudo code):

```javascript
myGraph.adjacencyList = {
    &quot;vertex1&quot;: {
        &quot;vertex2&quot;: &quot;label&quot;,
        &quot;vertex3&quot;: &quot;label&quot;,
        &quot;vertex4&quot;: &quot;anotherLabel&quot;
    }
}
```

However, to find if a vertex has an edge with a certain label, the operation becomes `O(|D|)` - where `|D|` (degrees) is the number edges a vertex has:

```javascript
// pseudo code
const getAdjacenciesConnectedByLabel = (graph, fromVertex, label) =&gt; Object.entries(graph.adjacencyList[fromVertex]).reduce((adjacenciesConnectedByLabel, [toVertex, edgeLabel]) =&gt; adjacenciesConnectedByLabel.concat(edgeLabel === label ? toVertex : []), []);

// this would then be used as follows:
getAdjacenciesConnectedByLabel(myGraph, &#39;vertex1&#39;, &#39;label&#39;);
// &gt;&gt;&gt; [&quot;vertex2&quot;, &quot;vertex3&quot;]
```

In order to make the operation `O(1)` (my goal), my first idea was to &quot;flip around&quot; how the adjacencies are stored:

```javascript
anotherGraph.adjacencyList = {
    &quot;vertex1&quot;: {
        &quot;label&quot;: [&quot;vertex2&quot;, &quot;vertex3&quot;],
        &quot;anotherLabel&quot;: [&quot;vertex4&quot;]
    }
}
const getAdjacenciesConnectedByLabel = (graph, fromVertex, label) =&gt; graph.adjacencyList[fromVertex][label];
```

However, now the operation to find if a vertex has an edge to another vertex (`isAdjacent`) becomes `O(|D|)` (if not worse - I actually don&#39;t totally know how to represent the following function in Big O notation - maybe `O(|D| * |L|)` where `|L|` is the number of labels per vertex):

```javascript
const isAdjacent = (graph, from, to) =&gt; Object.values(graph.adjacencyList[from]).reduce(bool, vertexSet) =&gt; !bool ? bool : vertexSet.includes(to), false);
